Fourhorn sculpin 
Myoxocephalus quadricornis
Order: Scorpaeniformes
Family: Cottidae

External appearance
The fourhorn sculpin is a bottom-dwelling fish found in both marine and fresh waters. One of the main features of the species are the four 'horns' or bony protuberances on its head. The skin is bare and covered with rows of small bony plates. Females can reach a length of 35 cm, while males can grow to 23 cm and 0.95 kg in weight.

Distribution
The fourhorn sculpin is found in the Northern Hemisphere. 

Diet
Mainly eats small crustaceans, occasionally eggs and small fish.

Development
Spawns on the bottom of the body of water, from November to February. Males build a spawning nest and guard the eggs for up to three months until they hatch. 

Fishing
Fourhorn sculpins are edible, but are of minor importance in commercial fishing. It is usually caught as bycatch. 

Interesting facts
This may have been one of the first marine fish species to enter the Baltic Sea basin around 10 000 years after the end of the last ice age.
